We found that when going to a show page for a record which is in two different exhibits, the solr record that's being rendered might not be the correct one.

For example, https://dpul.princeton.edu/happy_gall-entines_day/catalog/nz8060449 should come from the happy_gall-entines_day exhibit, but it's the one from PUDL0017 (you can tell by going to `/raw` and looking at the exhibit prefix..

Is the solr record that is rendered dictated by what DPUL collection was created first with that item (like your example link)? or is it random? we have items with multiple collection tags in figgy. I wonder what the consequences are?
A solr record is generated for each unique collection / resource pair. We need to fix the code to pull the right record.

dspace-development.title: Symplectic Elements: Missing Results for Specific Query

comments.body:
Okay I had somehow missed that you had moved the controllers out. I think my biggest use case was "I want to run all the controller tests" so this does make me happy.

I do worry a little that we still have `app/change_sets/`, `app/decorators`, `app/wayfinders` where not all the change sets decorators or wayfinders are found. But I like your point about keeping the change sets with the resource they apply to. That may help more with onboarding than having a more traditional file structure.

`app/resources` not being in `app/models` I guess is an amendment to point 1 on your list. Will we turn this into an ADR?

On the whole I am feeling good about this. Let's do it.

Code used to search for recording FileSets with un-characterized audio files:

```
class WavFileSets
  def uncharacterized_wav_file_sets
    recordings = query_service.custom_queries.find_by_property(property: "change_set", value: "recording", model: ScannedResource, lazy: false)
    file_sets = recordings.map do |recording|
      recording.decorate.file_sets.select do |file_set|
        file_set.mime_type == ["content/unknown"]
      end
    end.compact.flatten
    file_sets
  end

  def query_service
    @query_service ||= Valkyrie::MetadataAdapter.find(:postgres).query_service
  end
end
```

This was related to the `sendmail` configuration, as well as the `postfix` configuration for the server. The `sendmail` PID file was not being properly written to within the `/run` directory, while the `postfix` process should *not* have been run along with `sendmail` (as this was binding to port 25)
Also, please be aware that this was afflicting the production server environment as well. This should now also be resolved.
